1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:18,207
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:18,847 --> 00:00:35,322
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:35,341 --> 00:00:45,512
So, Sangha is the third refuge and it starts off by saying Supatipanno

4
00:00:46,183 --> 00:01:11,280
bhagavato sa-vakasango so that's of good conduct, the followers of the Blessed One then it says they are uju-patipanno, so of upright conduct nyaya-patipanno, wise conduct and samici-patipanno, dutiful conduct so those are the four descriptions, this supati

5
00:01:11,445 --> 00:01:39,191
which means, translates as good or virtuous people who follow, they're a special group of people, I will come to that in a minute but basically they are virtuous and good that's the supatipanno the ujjupatipanno, upright, I think refers really to their following of the rule that they're upright in that sense nyaya-patipanno, they're wise

6
00:01:39,576 --> 00:01:54,379
and samīci refers to the proper or true path that they're following so that's the qualities of the Sangha that we respect Sangha means community

7
00:01:54,763 --> 00:01:58,210
it normally refers to the ordained Sangha.

8
00:01:58,411 --> 00:02:09,352
If you go to Thailand or Sri Lanka or Burma, anywhere like that, and you say Sangha, they immediately think that you mean the ordained Sangha.

9
00:02:10,334 --> 00:02:12,418
But here it has a much wider meaning.

10
00:02:13,495 --> 00:02:18,663
Here it means anybody who has attained one of the four paths and fruits.

11
00:02:19,183 --> 00:02:21,967
And that's what the next section goes on to say.

12
00:02:22,489 --> 00:02:41,038
It says, So this is the order of disciples of the Blessed One, namely the four pairs of persons and the eight kinds of individuals.

13
00:02:41,861 --> 00:03:05,219
now that refers to their attainment remember there are four paths and fruits the normal explanation of that is that there's a moment in which one has the insight so you've entered into a path and then the fruit of it is the release from one of the fetters from one or more of the fetters

14
00:03:05,453 --> 00:03:17,558
So when we talk about the four persons, the four types of these followers of the Buddha, svākata, you see, the first one is the stream entrance.

15
00:03:18,341 --> 00:03:24,052
So what we mean by that is that they've had the experience of Nibbāna.

16
00:03:24,151 --> 00:03:26,334
The Buddha talks about it like a flash of lightning.

17
00:03:27,496 --> 00:03:30,520
But it's strong enough for them to have a systemic change.

18
00:03:32,062 --> 00:03:34,365
And you can't go back on that.

19
00:03:34,445 --> 00:03:35,727
It's a level of consciousness.

20
00:03:35,787 --> 00:03:37,469
It's a way of being in the world.

21
00:03:38,350 --> 00:03:44,139
And what you've undermined are three of these sannyājana, three of these fetters.

22
00:03:44,158 --> 00:03:48,284
And the first one is the view of the personality of self.

23
00:03:49,361 --> 00:04:14,948
the view of your personhood that you begin to realize that a personality is just a collection of habits and that when you're sitting in meditation you're actually watching these habits arise and pass away right there in front of you so that distance, that objectification of your personality is one of the realizations that it's not you it becomes you when you identify with it

24
00:04:15,198 --> 00:04:28,987
That identification, remember, is a loss of your awareness into the person, the personality, the five khandhas, the five aggregates.

25
00:04:30,418 --> 00:04:46,233
so that view has been sundered but it's not completely gone it's as though you've seen it but you're still held within its thrall it's like you've seen where the delusion lies but you still get deluded

26
00:04:48,307 --> 00:05:08,694
Also what goes is wrong rites and rituals, so the belief that just performing rites and rituals are going to actually get you in on the path itself, that they are a liberation in themselves, which doesn't mean to say that certain rites and rituals are not useful,

27
00:05:09,062 --> 00:05:15,110
For instance, in the West, I think, they do it also in the East, the sort of naming ceremonies.

28
00:05:15,350 --> 00:05:17,314
A little baby is brought, you see.

29
00:05:17,774 --> 00:05:28,509
In Burma, they offer the baby, they bring the baby to a monk, and the monk gives them a name, and then gives the parents a little coin to buy the baby.

30
00:05:30,411 --> 00:05:32,634
It's like a spiritual transaction.

31
00:05:32,653 --> 00:05:38,682
From now on, this little baby has a connection with this particular monk, for good or for evil.

32
00:05:40,466 --> 00:05:48,033
So there's that, now that of course doesn't, you're not going to liberate the little child at all, I mean, there's just a little connection that's made.

33
00:05:48,473 --> 00:05:55,579
So it's the same when we bow to the Buddha, Dhamma, Sangha, these things in themselves don't liberate, but they are supportive.

34
00:05:56,740 --> 00:06:08,971
And it's the same with chanting and all the various religious things that you see people do, they're just supports, often they're the juice of the practice, because vipassana can be a bit tough.

35
00:06:11,449 --> 00:06:24,851
and it's just recognizing that that's all so in other words they've come to know the path and the path is the undermining of that delusion which is seeking happiness in the sensual world that's the core of the problem

36
00:06:26,418 --> 00:06:29,081
And the third one is this skeptical doubt.

37
00:06:29,701 --> 00:06:36,689
So remember, skeptical doubt is not the same as the honest doubt of the philosopher, the wonder.

38
00:06:38,031 --> 00:06:48,161
We're not supposed to believe what the Buddha says, we're supposed to have that investigative faculty so that we can make it our own true, our own experience.

39
00:06:48,882 --> 00:06:52,206
But skeptical doubt, remember, is that doubt which stops you committing.

40
00:06:53,165 --> 00:07:14,987
your uncertainty your fear of commitment so that goes because now of course you've made it you've had that insight you see so that's the stream entrant the want returner which means that a person is drawn back into this life form undermines

41
00:07:15,084 --> 00:07:24,444
The next two, which is sensual pleasure as an attractive indulgence, and aversion, which remember has this twin business of hatred and fear.

42
00:07:25,045 --> 00:07:34,122
So those are only attenuated in the second level of attainment, the wants returner.

43
00:07:34,322 --> 00:07:38,749
And those are completely done away with, with the non-returner.

44
00:07:38,769 --> 00:07:46,098
And what that's basically saying is that that person is no longer drawn to this sensual life.

45
00:07:46,137 --> 00:07:47,620
There's no attraction there for it.

46
00:07:48,221 --> 00:07:55,189
It's much the same as, for instance, when we move out of teddy bears into toys.

47
00:07:56,110 --> 00:08:02,759
I mean, the teddy bear's still there, but you're not attracted to it anymore, or at least most people are.

48
00:08:02,740 --> 00:08:28,156
give up their teddy bears it's that sort of thing you see as you move into you know teenage and that sort of relationship with the world you give up your childish toys but you know that's not a problem you know because one feels there's a natural growth of our awareness and consciousness and our knowledge of the world so we're quite happy to leave those little toys behind

49
00:08:29,081 --> 00:08:38,197
But of course there comes a point where life doesn't seem to present anything else but sickness, old age and death, at which point you'd rather go back to your toys, you know.

50
00:08:39,393 --> 00:08:53,030
So apart from that, this non-returner, the anagami, just doesn't have anything in this life form that attracts them.

51
00:08:53,711 --> 00:09:01,001
What they are attracted to are these inner states of ecstasy, the rupa and arupa jhanas.

52
00:09:02,043 --> 00:09:03,105
And

53
00:09:03,085 --> 00:09:16,216
Those don't go until you finally, that indulgence in mental states, blissful mental states, doesn't go until you finally crack it at the end of the path, which is the Adahat, the fully liberated one.

54
00:09:16,365 --> 00:09:40,365
and with that there goes the core ignorance as to who we are like who am I once that core ignorance goes the self collapses and so the other two fetters conceit disappears so there's no comparison anymore and restlessness restlessness here I've always understood to mean

55
00:09:40,952 --> 00:09:54,614
all the hindrances that we suffer from, but as we grow in the spiritual life, they become less and less until they're just sort of little disturbances in the mind.

56
00:09:55,695 --> 00:09:57,398
They sort of lose their power over us.

57
00:09:58,659 --> 00:10:00,602
That's how I translate restlessness.

58
00:10:01,464 --> 00:10:06,432
But people will probably translate it more literally as restlessness.

59
00:10:07,393 --> 00:10:08,073
It's full stop.

60
00:10:09,909 --> 00:10:37,690
so those are your four pairs and every entrance into the path is the seeing of the path that's the Magga and the fruit of it is the collapse of one of these fetters that's why the word Nibbāna is often translated as unbinding, unshackling so it's the unshackling of this knowing from its unshacklement

61
00:10:37,669 --> 00:11:04,706
with the fetters and that's what you're doing every time you let go of something you're unshackling you're unbinding your consciousness your knowing from its delusion as to what it really is so now those four people can of course be both lay people and members of the monastic order

62
00:11:04,822 --> 00:11:34,339
so it transcends that sort of division and in the tradition people never actually say if somebody thinks or believes or knows that they're one of these paths they don't normally say it because once you say I am a Sotapanna or worse I am an Arahant then everybody and his dog proves you're not you just create enormous problems

63
00:11:36,445 --> 00:11:41,090
What people normally do is they express how they experience life.

64
00:11:42,912 --> 00:11:44,573
And then it's left up to the person to get.

65
00:11:44,914 --> 00:11:52,222
The Mahāsī said that these things are really just for one's own self-judgment about where one is.

66
00:11:53,144 --> 00:12:00,893
Of course the danger is that one either overestimates one's attainments and then there's usually a big disappointment coming up.

67
00:12:01,693 --> 00:12:02,875
But then that's humility.

68
00:12:04,879 --> 00:12:32,440
a humbling experience so now once we have those four types of persons which in a sense become an ideal an ideal we say that they're worthy of offerings and this is the requisites and it's the requisites so that they can continue with their practice or continue to be here as fully enlightened beings because of the good they do and we'll come to that as the last worthiness

69
00:12:33,989 --> 00:13:03,557
they're worthy of hospitality the four requisites and this is also in a sense part of it is of course you know food clothing shelter and medicine those are your four basic requisites of life aren't they food clothing shelter and medicine everything else is not necessary and the third one is they're worthy of gifts gift-making

70
00:13:10,118 --> 00:13:14,365
And the reason for that is that it also creates merit for you.

71
00:13:14,385 --> 00:13:26,868
So when you give to people whom you see are spiritually training, spiritually advanced, and you want to help them, it's also a good merit to you.

72
00:13:26,908 --> 00:13:34,422
In the East, of course, this gets corrupted as sort of merit-making, like a big bank account.

73
00:13:34,402 --> 00:13:38,726
you know, where you're storing up all these merits that when you die you enter into this beautiful heaven.

74
00:13:40,590 --> 00:13:47,238
I think it's wiser to think of it in terms of a growing of our own hearts in generosity.

75
00:13:49,640 --> 00:13:55,988
And the merit is the beauty of one's own generous, kind heart.

76
00:13:56,668 --> 00:13:58,991
That's your immediate merit, you might say.

77
00:14:00,423 --> 00:14:27,155
whether you get born into a heavenly realm or not is well it's to be hoped for and finally worthy of respect worthy of reverence and the reason for this is that they are an incomparable field of merit in the world an incomparable field of merit in other words they're great exemplars and one good example of that is mountaineering you see once you get

78
00:14:27,490 --> 00:14:35,610
somebody climbing Everest Hilary wasn't it Hilary no

79
00:14:37,143 --> 00:14:58,812
Edmund Henry that's it and Sherpa Tenzing yeah yeah though I believe Mallory did it because he was British when they when they reached Everest it opened the gates everybody who had a couple of legs could sort of well even with that couple of legs could actually make it

80
00:14:59,096 --> 00:15:27,822
it was there open to be climbed you see and of course there are lesser mountains, lesser peaks and every time somebody makes it, it opens up that avenue for somebody else to do it so they are exemplars and people who are well attained in the spiritual life are simply exemplars they stand as an example for other people and in that sense they are incomparable

81
00:15:27,802 --> 00:15:56,138
fields of merit because in a sense there's no greater gift is there to humanity than somebody who's attained especially attained the final path because that is the goal at least in Buddhist terms of where we're all trying to make to so in that sense they are the incomparable field of merit and that's why we honour them and pay respect to them

82
00:15:57,485 --> 00:16:00,932
So that concludes my little homily on the Sangha.

83
00:16:01,595 --> 00:16:04,562
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

84
00:16:05,123 --> 00:16:10,195
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

